<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4669798.stm>

Hong Kong S.A.R.: Avian Influenza Virus Alert
-----------------------------------------------
3 people have been taken to hospital in the Hong Kong S.A.R. of China
for observation, after having contact with a chicken feared to have
had avian influenza. The 3, who had contact with the bird after it
was brought to Hong Kong from China, are in an isolation ward. They
have shown no signs of infection, as further tests are carried out.
Hong Kong saw the 1st human cases of bird flu in 1997, but it has not
reported any human infections in the latest outbreak.
The 3 people live in a village near the border with China, and
officials said it was not clear whether the chicken contracted the
H5N1 virus in China or in the Hong Kong S.A.R. "So far, they have not
shown any symptoms of influenza -- no fever -- but we will have the
results of preliminary tests tomorrow," Thomas Tsang, director of the
government's Centre for Health Protection, told the Agence France
Presse (AFP) agency.
The bird flu alert came as people across the region celebrate the
lunar New Year, when families get together for special meals, often
involving chicken. The disease cannot be contracted by eating cooked
poultry, but those in close contact with sick birds are at risk. More
than 70 people in Southeast Asia are known to have died of bird flu
since late 2003
--
